{"title_page": "Westbeemster", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Westbeemster\n| settlement_type         = Town\n| other_name              = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name             = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = nl\n| image_skyline           = Beemster west2.JPG\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = Lourdesschool\n| image_flag              =\n| image_shield            =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = Map - NL - Municipality code 0370 (2009).svg\n| map_caption             =\n| image_map1              = Map NL - Beemster - Westbeemster.png\n| map_caption1            = The town centre (dark green) and the statistical district (light green) of Westbeemster in the municipality of Beemster.\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Netherlands -->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Netherlands\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Netherlands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of the Netherlands|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[North Holland]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of municipalities of the Netherlands|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Beemster]]\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| leader_party            =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|52|34|28|N|4|53|55|E|region:NL_type:city(360)|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          =\n| established_title       =\n| established_date        =\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = 360\n| population_as_of        = 2004\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in the Netherlands|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             =\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in the Netherlands|Dialing code]]\n| area_code               =\n| website                 =\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n'''Westbeemster''' is a town in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] province of [[North Holland]]. It is a part of the municipality of [[Beemster]], and lies about 9&nbsp;km northwest of [[Purmerend]].\n\nIn 2001, the town of Westbeemster had 117 inhabitants. The built-up area of the town was 0.04&nbsp;km\u00b2, and contained 40 residences.<ref name=\"CBS\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), ''Bevolkingskernen in Nederland 2001'' [http://www.cbs.nl/nl-NL/menu/themas/milieu-natuur-ruimte/ruimte/publicaties/cartografie-geografie/geografische-data/2001-bevolkingskernen-in-nederland.htm]. Statistics are for the continuous built-up area.</ref>  The larger statistical district \"Westbeemster\" has a population of around 360.<ref name=\"CBS2\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), ''Statline: Kerncijfers wijken en buurten 2003-2005'' [http://statline.cbs.nl/StatWeb/table.asp?D3=l&LA=nl&DM=SLNL&PA=70904ned&D1=9&D2=5380-5392]. As of 1 January 2005.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Beemster]]\n[[Category:Populated places in North Holland]]\n\n\n{{NorthHolland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Westbeemster\n| settlement_type         = Town\n| other_name              = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name             = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = nl\n| image_skyline           = Beemster west2.JPG\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           = Lourdesschool\n| image_flag              =\n| image_shield            =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = Map - NL - Municipality code 0370 (2009).svg\n| map_caption             =\n| image_map1              = Map NL - Beemster - Westbeemster.png\n| map_caption1            = The town centre (dark green) and the statistical district (light green) of Westbeemster in the municipality of Beemster.\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Netherlands -->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Netherlands\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Netherlands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of the Netherlands|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[North Holland]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of municipalities of the Netherlands|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Beemster]]\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| leader_party            =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|52|34|28|N|4|53|55|E|region:NL_type:city(360)|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          =\n| established_title       =\n| established_date        =\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = 360\n| population_as_of        = 2004\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in the Netherlands|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             =\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in the Netherlands|Dialing code]]\n| area_code               =\n| website                 =\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n'''Westbeemster''' is a town in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] province of [[North Holland]]. It is a part of the municipality of [[Beemster]], and lies about 9&nbsp;km northwest of [[Purmerend]].\n\nIn 2001, the town of Westbeemster had 117 inhabitants. The built-up area of the town was 0.04&nbsp;km\u00b2, and contained 40 residences.<ref name=\"CBS\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), ''Bevolkingskernen in Nederland 2001'' [http://www.cbs.nl/nl-NL/menu/themas/milieu-natuur-ruimte/ruimte/publicaties/cartografie-geografie/geografische-data/2001-bevolkingskernen-in-nederland.htm]. Statistics are for the continuous built-up area.</ref>  The larger statistical district \"Westbeemster\" has a population of around 360.<ref name=\"CBS2\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), ''Statline: Kerncijfers wijken en buurten 2003-2005'' [http://statline.cbs.nl/StatWeb/table.asp?D3=l&LA=nl&DM=SLNL&PA=70904ned&D1=9&D2=5380-5392]. As of 1 January 2005.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[Category:Beemster]]\n[[Category:Populated places in North Holland]]\n\n{{NorthHolland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westbeemster"}
{"title_page": "Julian Stefani", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2016}}\n'''Julian Ferdinand Stefani''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} (born 1939) is a former Australian politician.\n\nBefore entering politics, he was a managing director. In 1988 he was elected to the [[South Australian Legislative Council]] as a [[Liberal Party of Australia (South Australian Division)|Liberal]] member. He held his seat until his retirement in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Pages/default.aspx|title=Hon. Julian Stefani|access-date=24 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529082854/https://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Pages/default.aspx|archive-date=29 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stefani, Julian}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the South Australian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Australia-Liberal-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2016}}\n'''Julian Ferdinand Stefani''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} (born 1939) is a former Australian politician.\n\nBefore entering politics, he was a managing director. In 1988 he was elected to the [[South Australian Legislative Council]] as a [[Liberal Party of Australia (South Australian Division)|Liberal]] member. He held his seat until his retirement in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Pages/default.aspx|title=Hon. Julian Stefani|access-date=24 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529082854/https://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Pages/default.aspx|archive-date=29 May 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stefani, Julian}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the South Australian Legislative Council]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Australia-Liberal-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Timrollpickering", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:stub clean up, addedunderlinkedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_Stefani"}
{"title_page": "Westbroek", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Westbroek\n| settlement_type         = Village\n| other_name              = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name             = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = nl\n| image_skyline           =\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_flag              =\n| image_shield            =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = LocatieDeBilt.png\n| map_caption             =\n| image_map1              = Map NL - De Bilt - Westbroek.png\n| map_caption1            = The town centre (dark green) and the statistical district (light green) of Westbroek in the municipality of De Bilt.\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Netherlands -->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Netherlands\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Netherlands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of the Netherlands|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Utrecht (province)|Utrecht]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of municipalities of the Netherlands|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[De Bilt]]\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| leader_party            =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|52|9|0|N|5|8|0|E|region:NL_type:city(990)|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          =\n| established_title       =\n| established_date        =\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = 990\n| population_as_of        = 2004\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in the Netherlands|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = 3615\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in the Netherlands|Dialing code]]\n| area_code               =\n| website                 =\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n[[File:Westbroek, de Nederlands Hervormde kerk RM26509 foto3 2012-05-28 17.36.JPG|Westbroek, reformed church|thumb|200px|left]]\n'''Westbroek''' is a village in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] province of [[Utrecht (province)|Utrecht]]. It is a part of the municipality of [[De Bilt]], and lies about 6&nbsp;km northwest of [[Bilthoven]].\n\nIn 2001, the village of Westbroek had 510 inhabitants. The built-up area of the village was 0.12&nbsp;km\u00b2, and contained 178 residences.<ref name=\"CBS\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), ''Bevolkingskernen in Nederland 2001'' [http://www.cbs.nl/nl-NL/menu/themas/milieu-natuur-ruimte/ruimte/publicaties/cartografie-geografie/geografische-data/2001-bevolkingskernen-in-nederland.htm]. Statistics are for the continuous built-up area.</ref>\nThe statistical area \"Westbroek\", which also includes the peripheral parts of the village, as well as the surrounding countryside and the village of [[Achttienhoven (Utrecht)|Achttienhoven]], has a population of around 1,300.<ref name=\"CBS2\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), [http://statline.cbs.nl/ ''Statline: Kerncijfers wijken en buurten 2003-2005'']. As of 1 January 2005.</ref>\n\nWestbroek consists mainly of a [[ribbon farm|ribbon of farms]] along a dike. The village is surrounded by a number of [[polder]]s: the Polder Westbroek, the Kerkeindse Polder, and the Polder Achttienhoven in the north, and the Molenpolder and Polder de Kooi in the south. The Molenpolder is a nature reserve.\n\n==History==\nWestbroek used to be a separate municipality. It merged into Maartensdijk in 1957, and has been a part of the De Bilt municipality since 2001.\n\nThe church dates from 1467.\n\nOn 26 December 1481, Westbroek was the site of a major battle, known as the [[Battle of Westbroek]], between the armies of the prince-bishopric of Utrecht and Holland, with Holland winning a decisive victory.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Kuypers|Westbroek|ut}} Map of the former municipality in 1868.\n\n{{Commons category|Westbroek, Utrecht|position=left}}\n\n{{Dutch municipality De Bilt}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Utrecht (province)]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities of Utrecht (province)]]\n[[Category:De Bilt]]\n\n\n{{Utrecht-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Westbroek\n| settlement_type         = Village\n| other_name              = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name             = <!-- if different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = nl\n| image_skyline           =\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_flag              =\n| image_shield            =\n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = LocatieDeBilt.png\n| map_caption             =\n| image_map1              = Map NL - De Bilt - Westbroek.png\n| map_caption1            = The town centre (dark green) and the statistical district (light green) of Westbroek in the municipality of De Bilt.\n| pushpin_map             = <!-- Netherlands -->\n| pushpin_label_position  =\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in the Netherlands\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Netherlands]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of the Netherlands|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Utrecht (province)|Utrecht]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of municipalities of the Netherlands|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[De Bilt]]\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| leader_party            =\n| coordinates             = {{coord|52|9|0|N|5|8|0|E|region:NL_type:city(990)|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| elevation_m             =\n| elevation_min_m         =\n| elevation_max_m         =\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          =\n| established_title       =\n| established_date        =\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = 990\n| population_as_of        = 2004\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in the Netherlands|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = 3615\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in the Netherlands|Dialing code]]\n| area_code               =\n| website                 =\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n[[File:Westbroek, de Nederlands Hervormde kerk RM26509 foto3 2012-05-28 17.36.JPG|Westbroek, reformed church|thumb|200px|left]]\n'''Westbroek''' is a village in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] province of [[Utrecht (province)|Utrecht]]. It is a part of the municipality of [[De Bilt]], and lies about 6&nbsp;km northwest of [[Bilthoven]].\n\nIn 2001, the village of Westbroek had 510 inhabitants. The built-up area of the village was 0.12&nbsp;km\u00b2, and contained 178 residences.<ref name=\"CBS\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), ''Bevolkingskernen in Nederland 2001'' [http://www.cbs.nl/nl-NL/menu/themas/milieu-natuur-ruimte/ruimte/publicaties/cartografie-geografie/geografische-data/2001-bevolkingskernen-in-nederland.htm]. Statistics are for the continuous built-up area.</ref>\nThe statistical area \"Westbroek\", which also includes the peripheral parts of the village, as well as the surrounding countryside and the village of [[Achttienhoven (Utrecht)|Achttienhoven]], has a population of around 1,300.<ref name=\"CBS2\">Statistics Netherlands (CBS), [http://statline.cbs.nl/ ''Statline: Kerncijfers wijken en buurten 2003-2005'']. As of 1 January 2005.</ref>\n\nWestbroek consists mainly of a [[ribbon farm|ribbon of farms]] along a dike. The village is surrounded by a number of [[polder]]s: the Polder Westbroek, the Kerkeindse Polder, and the Polder Achttienhoven in the north, and the Molenpolder and Polder de Kooi in the south. The Molenpolder is a nature reserve.\n\n==History==\nWestbroek used to be a separate municipality. It merged into Maartensdijk in 1957, and has been a part of the De Bilt municipality since 2001.\n\nThe church dates from 1467.\n\nOn 26 December 1481, Westbroek was the site of a major battle, known as the [[Battle of Westbroek]], between the armies of the prince-bishopric of Utrecht and Holland, with Holland winning a decisive victory.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Kuypers|Westbroek|ut}} Map of the former municipality in 1868.\n\n\n{{Commons category|Westbroek, Utrecht|position=left}}\n\n{{Dutch municipality De Bilt}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Utrecht (province)]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities of Utrecht (province)]]\n[[Category:De Bilt]]\n\n\n{{Utrecht-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westbroek"}
{"title_page": "Western Magpies Australian Football Club", "text_new": "{{Dablink|\"Sherwood Magpies AFC\" (the abbreviated name of the club), \"Taringa AFC\", \"Western Districts AFC\", \"Sherwood AFC\", \"West Brisbane AFC\" (previous names of the club) and \"Sherwood Junior AFC\" (the affiliated junior club) all redirect here. For the \"Western Suburbs Magpies Australian Football Club\" club based in [[Sydney, Australia]] please see [[Western Suburbs Magpies AFC]].}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox Australian football club\n| clubname           = Sherwood Magpies\n| image              = Western magpies afc logo.png\n| image size = 200px\n| color1 = #000000 \n| color2 = #ffffff\n| color3 = solid #ffffff\n| fullname           = Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club\n| nickname           = ''Magpies''\n| founded            = {{Start date and age|1991}}\n| league             = [[Queensland Australian Football League]]\n| firstseason        = 1999\n| ground             = McCarthy Homes Sherwood AFC, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]]\n| song               = Good Old Sherwood Club Forever\n| president          = Bruce McNichoal\n| coach              = Glenn Humphrey\n| captain            = Lachlan Woods\n| season             = 2016\n| premierships    = \n| kit_alt1        = \n| pattern_b1      = _portadelaide_bars\n| pattern_sh1     = \n| pattern_so1     = \n| body1           = ffffff\n| shorts1         = 000000\n| socks1          = 000000\n| pattern_name1   = <!--optional, default: Home -->\n| kit_alt2        = \n| pattern_b2      = \n| pattern_sh2     = \n| pattern_so2     = \n| body2           = \n| shorts2         = \n| socks2          = \n| pattern_name2   = <!--optional, default: Away -->\n  | url       = [http://www.westernmagpies.com.au/ westernmagpies.com.au]\n  | jumper     =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club''' is the senior [[Australian rules football]] club of the western suburbs of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]] which competes in Division One of the [[AFL Queensland State League|AFLQ State League]]. The club is based at McCarthy Homes Oval, 41 Chelmer st, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]],<ref name=\"fullpointsfooty.net\">http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/western_magpies.htm Sherwood Magpies</ref> at the same grounds as the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]] and fields a team in the [[AFLQ]] senior, reserve, under 18 and women's grade competitions. The Western Magpies AFC provides a focal point for talented players from all of the junior clubs that lie within [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane's]] western suburbs (Collingwood Park, Ferny Grove, Forest Lake, Kenmore, Jindalee, Moorooka, Sherwood, Southern Redbacks, Springfield Lakes, Wests Juniors, Yeronga). The club aims to provide a pathway into the [[Australian Football League|AFL]] for players from these junior clubs, develop the network of surrounding senior and junior [[Australian rules football]] clubs, and provide a fun, friendly, family oriented hub for local football in the western suburbs.<ref>http://www.sherwoodafc.com/inside.htm A Brief History of the Black & White</ref> The '''Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club''' and [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]] are sponsored by Tradelink (major sponsor), [[Hog's Breath Cafe]] and Cleanway (secondary sponsors).<ref>http://www.sherwoodafc.com/sponsors.htm Magpie Sponsors</ref>\n\nThere have been a number of senior clubs ([[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa]], [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]], [[Sherwood Australian Football Club|Sherwood]], and [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club|West Brisbane]]) based within the western suburbs of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]] that have competed in the highest division of local football. These clubs were all forced out of existence over time, and the Sherwood Magpies AFC resembles a culmination of the area's historical and continuing football presence and strength. The current club has been playing in Division Two of the [[AFL Queensland State League]] since 2004, but is being promoted into Division One from the commencement of the 2009 season under the guidance of President Brian Knight, Senior Coach Paul Grentell and Club Development Manager Anthony McDonald.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?c=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6786642 Anthony McDonald Joins Magpies</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club was formed as the State League representative of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs, incorporating the history of the previous clubs to compete in the [[AFL Queensland State League]].\n\n===Taringa AFC===\nA '''Taringa Football Club''' competed in the QFL (an early form of the [[AFL Queensland State League]]) in the 1920 season. The club only appeared in the State competition for that single season, but resurfaced by entering the newly titled [[QANFL]] in 1931. The club's emblem was the [[bulldog]], and the club colours were maroon and white. Despite making it to five grand finals '''Taringa''' was unable to secure a premiership, but it produced two [[De Little Medal]]ists in C.Vigden (1939) and Doug Pittard (1940). '''Taringa''' changed its name to the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club]] in 1946.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/western_districts.htm Western Districts</ref>\n\n===Western Districts AFC===\nThe '''Western Districts Australian Football Club''' came into existence in 1946 when the [[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa Football Club]] changed its name to incorporate the whole of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs. '''Western Districts''' kept the emblem (the [[bulldog]]) and colours (maroon and white) of [[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa]] and were originally based at Oakman Park, [[Toowong, Queensland|Toowong]] but moved to Chelmer Oval, Queenscroft st, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]] in 1971. The club continued to grow steadily, finishing in third place in 1951, and losing to [[Mayne Australian Football Club|Mayne]] by merely one point in the 1952 grand final. The club learned from their narrow loss, defeating Windsor and Sandgate respectively in the 1953 and 1954 grand finals to secure their first and second premierships. '''Western Districts''' were unable to qualify for the finals between the years of 1956 and 1962, before suffering consecutive grand final losses at the hands of [[Mayne Australian Football Club|Mayne]] in 1966 and 1967. The club's next, and last ever, grand final appearances came consecutively in 1977, 1978 and 1979. The '''Bulldogs''' narrowly won premierships by 5 points against Wilston Grange in 1977, and by 4 points against [[Zillmere Eagles Australian Football Club|Windsor/Zillmere]] in 1978, before losing what would be their last grand final appearance to [[Sandgate Australian Football Club|Sandgate]] in 1979. '''Western Districts''' eventually merged with [[Sherwood Australian Football Club|Sherwood]] in 1991 to form the [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club]]. The '''Western Districts Australian Football Club''' had a number of very successful players in their midst throughout their existence. Doug Pittard won two [[Grogan Medal]]s during his time at the club to go with his [[De Little Medal]] he won with [[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa]], and played a handful of games for the [[Footscray Football Club|Footscray]] reserves. Owen Backwell was also a dual [[Grogan Medal]]ist for the '''Bulldogs''', who topped the league goal kicking in 1977, played over 300 games for the club, including the 1977 and 1978 premierships, and had a short stint with the [[Fitzroy Football Club]]. Ray Hughson topped the league goal kicking while playing for [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]] a remarkable six times (1958, 1959, 1962\u201365), while [[Gavin Crosisca]] (over 250 [[Australian Football League|AFL]] games for [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]]), Ray Smith (over 100 [[Australian Football League|VFL]] games for [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] and [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne]]), and Gary Shaw ([[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]] and the [[Brisbane Bears]], and still coaches at the Western Magpies) all went on to play in the [[Australian Football League|VFL/AFL]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref>http://www.footypedia.com/00000517.htm Western Districts Football Club</ref>\n\n===Sherwood AFC===\nThe '''Sherwood Australian Football Club''' developed out of the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]], which was formed in 1956. As the junior club grew in size, there was a desire to have a direct senior team for the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club|Sherwood JAFC]], which saw the '''Sherwood AFC''' formed to compete in the Metropolitan Division of the [[AFL Queensland State League|QAFL]]. The club was based at Chelmer Oval, 41 Chelmer st, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]], directly next to the Queenscroft st ground of the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]], which is the current home of the Western Magpies. The club took on the black and white stripes of their junior club as well as the emblem of the [[magpie]], both of which are still thoroughly attached to the club to the current day thanks to the winning of a coin toss with [[Southport Australian Football Club|Southport]] (who had previously had the same colours and emblem) upon the entry of both clubs to the [[AFL Queensland State League|QAFL]] in 1983. This occurred after '''Sherwood''' managed to work their way up through the divisions, after winning eight first division flags in a row they earned their 1983 promotion into the [[AFL Queensland State League|QAFL]]. In 1991 '''Sherwood AFC''' merged with the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]] to form the [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club]], which could be a single footballing force in [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs. Players of particular note for the '''Sherwood AFC''' include [[John Rantall]], the 336 game [[Sydney Swans|South Melbourne]], [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] and [[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]] [[Australian Football League|VFL]] veteran who coached '''Sherwood''' in their debut season in the [[QAFL]], and 1983 [[Grogan Medal]] winner, Bill Pierce, whom the Western Magpies best and fairest is named after.<ref name=\"sherwoodafc.com\">http://www.sherwoodafc.com/inside.htm A Brief History Of The Black & White</ref>\n\n===West Brisbane AFC===\nA merger between the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts AFC]] and the [[Sherwood Australian Football Club|Sherwood AFC]] in 1991 saw a single senior force in the western suburbs formed in the form of the '''West Brisbane Australian Football Club'''. The merged club adopted the maroon and white colours of [Western Districts Australian Football Club] with the jersey design of the Port Adelaide Magpies football club, played out of Chelmer Oval, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]] and were nicknamed The '''Warriors'''. The club was successful in winning a premiership in the 1996 season, comfortably defeating [[Mt Gravatt Australian Football Club|Mt Gravatt]] 17.10 (112) to 8.10 (58), with Corey Lambert claiming that year's [[Grogan Medal]]. Unfortunately, due to financial reasons '''West Brisbane''' were unable to compete in the following year's competition and had a few seasons out of the State competition before returning as the re-branded Western Magpies Australian Football Club in 2001.<ref name=\"fullpointsfooty.net\" /><ref>http://www.footypedia.com/00000512.htm West Brisbane Football Club</ref>\n\n===The Current Club===\n\nThe [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club]] that disbanded at the end of 1997 reformed in 1999 under the name of the Western Magpies Australian Football Club and in 2001 re-entered the [[QAFL]]<ref name=\"fullpointsfooty.net\" /> which had merged with its [[Gold Coast, Australia|Gold Coast]] equivalent to become the [[AFL Queensland State League]]. After four years of mediocre on-field performances and financial struggles, when the [[AFL Queensland|AFLQ]] decided to undertake a major re-shuffling of the leagues in 2004 to create a two tier [[AFL Queensland|State League]] competition the Western Magpies were relegated to the newly created Division Two. Paul Grentell was appointed the club's senior coach, and the '''Magpies''' set about strengthening every aspect of the football club in the hopes of returning to Division One. The senior team narrowly missed out on a place in the 2005 Division Two grand final, but were successful in reaching the grand final in 2006, 2007 and 2008. The Western Magpies defeated the [[Noosa Australian Football Club|Noosa Tigers]] in the 2006 decider, before losing to the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] in the final game of 2007. Despite losing the 2007 grand final, it was announced at the end of that year that the Western Magpies would be returning to Division One of the [[AFL Queensland State League|State League]] in 2009. The Magpies rebounded from their 2007 loss to [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach]] to end the Lions 38-game winning streak at their [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]] home ground during the 2008 home and away season, and followed this up by defeating the Lions again in a thrilling grand final.<ref name=\"sportingpulse.com\">http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6798374&sectionID=56344 Western Magpies Win 2008 Div 2 Premiership</ref> This capped the club's time in Division Two off nicely, leaving them with two premierships (2006 & 2008) and three grand final appearances (2006\u20132008) from their four years in lower division. During this four-year period, the reserves team played in the Division Two grand final (each year 2005\u20132008), winning premierships in 2005, 2006 and 2007, while the under 18 and women's teams both continued to participate in Division One of their competitions.\n\nAs of the beginning of Season 2020 in the Queensland Australian Football League\n\n==Links To Other Local Clubs==\nThe Western Magpies enjoy close relationships with all of the junior and senior clubs within [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs in their role as the focal point for football ball in the area. All junior clubs within the area are encouraged to promote the Western Magpies as the pathway into the [[Australian Football League|AFL]] for young players in the western suburbs. In a similar way, the club also relates closely with the surrounding senior clubs, as they also provide a pathway for players to play at a standard of football that best suits their ability.<ref name=\"sherwoodafc.com\" /> In particular, the Western Magpies work closely with the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]] and the [[Kenmore Australian Football Club]]. The junior clubs within the western suburbs that the Western Magpies work with include;\n*Collingwood Park\n*Ferny Grove\n*Forest Lake\n*The Gap\n*Kenmore\n*Jindalee\n*Moggill\n*Moorooka\n*Park Ridge\n*Sherwood\n*Southern Redbacks\n*Springfield Lakes\n*Wests Juniors\n*Yeronga\n\n===Sherwood Junior AFC===\nThe senior Western Magpies club is based out of the same grounds and facilities as the Sherwood Junior AFC. The two clubs are both affiliated with the Sherwood Football social club, and Sherwood Junior AFC acts as one of the many local feeder clubs to the Western Magpies, with many juniors moving up from the Sherwood juniors into the senior club. The '''Sherwood Junior AFC''''s aim is to produce quality players to graduate into football with the Western Magpies, and eventually to the [[Australian Football League|AFL]].<ref name=\"sherwoodafc.com\" /> The official website of the '''Sherwood Junior AFC''' is located at [http://www.sherwoodafc.com/ www.sherwoodafc.com].\n\n===Kenmore AFC===\nThe [[Kenmore Australian Football Club]] are a separate club who play in the [http://www.aflq.com.au/index.php?id=911 QFA South competition].[[Kenmore Australian Football Club|The Kenmore Bears]] and the Western Magpies enjoy a close relationship that sees players transfer between the two clubs in order to play the best possible level of football. The two clubs' grounds are situated next to each other in [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]], with [[Kenmore Australian Football Club|Kenmore]] playing out of the Queenscroft st grounds that were once those of the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club]]. In 2008 these grounds were closed for redevelopment, and [[Kenmore Australian Football Club|Kenmore]] played their all of their home games for that season on the Western Magpies field.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-4711-0-0-0&sID=56333&articleID=5033895&news_task=DETAIL New Alliance Ensures Bright Future</ref> The official website of the [[Kenmore Australian Football Club|Kenmore Bears]] is located at [http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?sportid=4&client=1-109-37543-0-0 www.kenmore.aflq.com.au].\n\n==2008 season==\nThe Western Magpies Australian Football Club competed in the Pineapple Hotel Cup in 2008, the Division Two competition of the [[AFL Queensland State League]]. The president for 2008 was Matthew Vowles, who entered the position in 2007, and the captain Chris Mihalopolous, a junior of the '''Sherwood Junior AFC'''. Paul Grentell, who took over the position as senior coach in 2004, was to coach the senior team in 2008, assisted by Peter McClennan (reserves coach), Hadyn Dowley, Quentin Johnson and Brian Millar. After being defeated by the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club]] in the 2007 grand final, the Western Magpies went through the 2008 home and away season with fifteen wins out of eighteen games to sit second on the ladder to the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] before the commencement of the finals series.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/team_info.cgi?c=1-109-34766-65372-6259025&a=ROUND Pineapple Hotel Cup Seniors Results 2008</ref> The Magpies's only losses were against [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin]] (Round 1), [[Coolangatta Tweed Heads Football Club|Coolangatta Tweed Head]] (Round 2) and [[Burleigh Football Club|Burleigh]] (Round 16), and one of the most memorable victories came in Round 14, when the Magpies defeated the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] 18.8 (116) to 5.16 (46) to end the Lions's 34-game winning streak.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-4711-0-0-0&sID=56333&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=5911606 Magpies Make A Statement</ref> The Western Magpies and the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] both made it through the finals series into the 2008 [[AFL Queensland State League]] grand final for a rematch of the previous year's grand final. The two clubs fought out a tough contest, which saw the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Lions]] lead throughout the first three quarters of the game. The Magpies lifted during the third quarter to close in on the minor premiers, and managed to kick six goals to two in a thrilling final quarter to take out a nail biting decider, 16.8 (104) to 14.17 (101).<ref>http://westside-news.whereilive.com.au/sport/story/pies-in-upset-finals-victory/ Pies In Upset Finals Victory</ref> The Magpies reserves went through the home and away season with only two losses, to Wilston Grange and [[Burleigh Australian Football Club|Burleigh]]. This left the team on top of the ladder, one game clear of their closest rivals.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/comp_info.cgi?a=LADDER&round=18&client=1-109-0-66115-0&pool=1 Pineapple Hotel Cup Reserves Ladder Round 18 2008</ref> The reserves won their way straight through to the grand final, where they were unable to make it four consecutive Division Two premierships, being soundly beaten by [[Aspley Australian Football Club|Aspley]] 10.8 (68) to 21.7 (133).<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-109-0-66115-0&pool=1001&round=18&a=ROUND Pineapple Hotel Cup Reserves Finals Round 6 Results 2008</ref> The Western Magpies under 18 team won three of their matches curing the season, and were unable to secure a place in the finals.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/comp_info.cgi?a=LADDER&round=16&client=1-109-0-69696-0&pool=1 Under 18 Division One Ladder Round 16 2008</ref>\n\n===Award Winners===\n\nThe following awards were presented at the Western Magpies Australian Football Club presentation night on 18 October.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6919627&sectionID=56344</ref>\n\n====Seniors====\n\n*Bill Pierce Medal for Best & Fairest \u2013 Val Pope\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Richard Wenham\n*Most Consistent \u2013 Greg Friis\n*BG Award \u2013 Tim McEvoy\n*Rookie of the Year \u2013 Gerard Moore\n*Best Back \u2013 Mark Dowley\n*Best Midfielder \u2013 Richard Wenham\n*Best Forward \u2013 Adam Gillespie\n*Best Finals Player \u2013 Luke Scott\n*Best on Ground in the Grand Final \u2013 James Rozynski\n\n====Reserves====\n*Best & Fairest \u2013 Jye Spencer\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Blake McClennan\n*Most Consistent \u2013 Luke Knight\n*Most Improved Player \u2013 Dominic Beer\n*Best Back \u2013 Scott Hughes\n*Best Midfielder \u2013 Matthew Page\n*Best Forward \u2013 Jay Baker\n*Best Finals Player \u2013 Cameron Thomas\n\n====Under 18====\n*Maurie McNamee Medal for Best & Fairest \u2013 Mark Stratton\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Daniel Massey\n*Most Consistent \u2013 Cory Colhoun\n*Most Improved \u2013 Jordan Patterson\n*Encouragement Award \u2013 Matthew Green\n*Russell Green Memorial Trophy for Coach of the Year \u2013 [[Gary Shaw (Australian footballer)|Gary Shaw]]\n\n==2009 season==\n\nIt was announced at the end of 2007 that the Western Magpies would be returning to Division One of the [[AFL Queensland State League]] from 2009.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-4711-0-0-0&sID=56333&articleID=4885742&news_task=DETAIL Western Magpies Set FOr 2009 Return To State League</ref> After achieving successful results, it was felt that the Magpies had made enough progress to warrant a western suburbs presence in the State League. In 2008 the club hired Anthony McDonald as Club Development Officer to assist in the progression up to the [[AFL Queensland State League|State League]],<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?c=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6786642 Anthony McDonald Joins The Magpies</ref> and began interviewing potential players to bolster their playing list for the 2009 season. The club's existing young talent was bolstered by the signings of 2007 Tasmanian under 18 representative Matt Dillon <ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=7030105&sectionID=56344 Tassie Magpie Becomes QLD Magpie</ref> and former [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] rookie and Western Magpie junior Ed McDonnell<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=7080688&sectionID=56344 Former St Kilda Rookie Returns To Magpies Nest</ref> but overall the Magpies failed to recruit many top level players. The Western Magpies senior squad were put through a tough pre-season program before hosting the [[Redland Australian Football Club|Redland Bombers]] in round one of the season. The Magpies seniors team were unable to get a victory in their first match in the [[AFL Queensland State League]], losing by 48 points in a match that has so far set the tone for their season. The Western Magpies seniors are currently yet to record a victory in the 2009 season, as seen in the table of results below;\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Round\n! Venue\n! Opposition\n! Magpies Score\n! Opposition Score\n|-\n| 1\n| Chelmer\n| [[Redland Australian Football Club|Redland]]\n| 11.7.73\n| 17.19.121\n|-\n| 2\n| Cooke-Murphy Oval\n| [[Labrador Australian Football Club|Labrador Tigers]]\n| 4.6.30\n| 22.19.151\n|-\n| 3\n| Chelmer\n| [[Broadbeach Australian Football Club|Broadbeach Cats]]\n| 15.6.96\n| 21.11.137\n|-\n| 4\n| Fankhauser Reserve\n| [[Southport Australian Football Club|Southport Sharks]]\n| 2.7.19\n| 28.12.180\n|-\n| 5\n| Chelmer\n| [[Aspley Australian Football Club|Aspley Hornets]]\n| 17.9.111\n| 18.19.118\n|-\n| 6\n| Chelmer\n| [[Morningside Australian Football Club|Morningside Panthers]]\n| 10.7.67\n| 31.13.199\n|-\n| 7\n| [[Traeger Park]]\n| [[Northern Territory Football Club|Northern Territory Thunder]]\n| 6.7.43\n| 26.13.169\n|-\n| 8\n| Chelmer\n| [[Brisbane Lions]]\n| 11.10.76\n| 16.9.105\n|-\n| 9\n| Esplen Oval\n| [[Morningside Australian Football Club|Morningside Panthers]]\n| 5.5.35\n| 27.21.183\n|-\n| 10\n| Dittmer Park\n| [[Mt Gravatt Australian Football Club|Mount Gravatt Vultures]]\n| 4.5.29\n| 25.16.166\n|-\n| 11\n| Chelmer\n| [[Northern Territory Football Club|Northern Territory Thunder]]\n| 10.11.71\n| 16.16.112\n|-\n| 12\n| Chelmer\n| [[Labrador Australian Football Club|Labrador Tigers]]\n| 14.10.94\n| 18.12.120\n|-\n| 13\n| Merrimac Oval\n| [[Broadbeach Australian Football Club|Broadbeach Cats]]\n| 6.10.46\n| 15.18.108\n|-\n| 14\n| Graham Rd\n| [[Aspley Australian Football Club|Aspley Hornets]]\n| 12.9.81\n| 20.13.133\n|-\n| 15\n| Chelmer\n| [[Southport Australian Football Club|Southport Sharks]]\n| 5.7.37\n| 15.20.110\n|-\n| 16\n| Chelmer\n| [[Mt Gravatt Australian Football Club|Mount Gravatt Vultures]]\n| 12.8.80\n| 17.12.144\n|-\n| 17\n| Victoria Point Oval\n| [[Redland Australian Football Club|Redland]]\n| 12.7.79\n| 15.16.106\n|-\n| 18\n| [[The Gabba]]\n| [[Brisbane Lions]]\n| 8.11.59\n| 32.19.211\n|}\n\n===Seniors Awards===\n\n*Bill Pierce Medal for Best & Fairest \u2013 Ben Heffernan-Roper\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Chris Judson\n*BG Award \u2013 Luke Scott\n*Rookie of the Year \u2013 Ben Jaenke-Cain\n*Best Back \u2013 Ed McDonnell\n*Best Midfielder \u2013 Ben Heffernan-Roper\n*Best Forward \u2013 Josh Barton\n*Hard luck story - Chris McClennan\n\n==Honour List==\n\n=== Senior Premierships===\n\n'''Queensland Australian Football League''' <ref name=\"ReferenceB\">http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/qafl_summary_chart.htm QAFL Summary Chart</ref>\n\n*1953 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1954 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1977 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1978 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1996 \u2013 West Brisbane\n\n'''AFL Queensland State League \u2013 Division Two'''\n\n*2006 \u2013 Western Magpies <ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34756-0-0&sID=55272&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=4873326&sectionID=55272 Tigers Go Down Fighting In Grand Finals</ref>\n*2008 \u2013 Western Magpies <ref name=\"sportingpulse.com\" />\n\n'''SEQAFL Division One - PHC'''\n*''2012''\n\n===AFL/VFL Listed Players===\n\n*[[Ray Smith (Australian footballer)|Ray Smith]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon Bombers]] (1971\u20131975, 77 games 1 goal), [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne Demons]] (1975\u20131976, 27 games 1 goal)\n*[[Gary Shaw (Australian footballer)|Gary Shaw]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood Magpies]] (1983\u20131986, 32 games 33 goals), [[Brisbane Bears]] (1987, 6 games 5 goals)\n*[[Craig Potter (Australian footballer)|Craig Potter]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Sydney Swans]] (1984\u20131990, 42 games 16 goals) [[Brisbane Bears]] (1991\u20131993, 13 games 3 goals)\n*[[Gavin Crosisca]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood Magpies]] (1987\u20132000, 246 games 64 goals)\n*[[Simon Luhrs]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Brisbane Bears]] (1991\u20131993, 12 games 0 goals)\n*[[Simon Hose]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Sydney Swans]] (1986\u20131988, 0 games 0 goals) [[Brisbane Bears]] (1989\u20131990, 5 games, 2 goals)\n*[[Marty Pask]] (Western Magpies) \u2013 [[Brisbane Lions]] (2006, 8 games 4 goals), [[Western Bulldogs]] (2007, 0 games 0 goals)\n\n===Grogan Medallists===\n\nNote: Prior to 1946, the [[Grogan Medal]] was titled the De Little Medal.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\" />\n\n*1939 \u2013 C.Vigden (Taringa)\n*1940 \u2013 D.Pittard (Taringa)\n*1946 \u2013 D.Pittard (Western Districts)\n*1947 \u2013 D.Pittard (Western Districts)\n*1956 \u2013 [[Tom Pelly|T.Pelly]] (Western Districts)\n*1958 \u2013 A.Stewart (Western Districts)\n*1971 \u2013 O.Backwell (Western Districts)\n*1975 \u2013 O.Backwell (Western Districts)\n*1977 \u2013 P.Taylor (Western Districts)\n*1983 \u2013 W.Pierce (Sherwood)\n*1996 \u2013 C.Lambert (West Brisbane)\n\n===League Leading Goalkickers===\n\n*1958 \u2013 R.Hughson (Western Districts) [71]\n*1959 \u2013 R.Hughson (Western Districts) [114]\n*1962 \u2013 R.Hughson (Western Districts) [105]\n*1963 \u2013 R.Hughson (Western Districts) [109]\n*1964 \u2013 R.Hughson (Western Districts) [111]\n*1965 \u2013 R.Hughson (Western Districts) [90]\n*1977 \u2013 O.Backwell (Western Districts) [93]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.westernmagpies.com.au/ Official website]\n\n{{AFL Queensland State League Clubs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Queensland State Football League clubs|Western Magpies]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football clubs in Brisbane]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1991]]\n[[Category:Chelmer, Queensland]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Dablink|\"Sherwood Magpies AFC\" (the abbreviated name of the club), \"Taringa AFC\", \"Western Districts AFC\", \"Sherwood AFC\", \"West Brisbane AFC\" (previous names of the club) and \"Sherwood Junior AFC\" (the affiliated junior club) all redirect here. For the \"Western Suburbs Magpies Australian Football Club\" club based in [[Sydney, Australia]] please see [[Western Suburbs Magpies AFC]].}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Infobox Australian football club\n| clubname           = Sherwood Magpies\n| image              = Western magpies afc logo.png\n| image size = 200px\n| color1 = #000000 \n| color2 = #ffffff\n| color3 = solid #ffffff\n| fullname           = Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club\n| nickname           = ''Magpies''\n| founded            = {{Start date and age|1991}}\n| league             = [[Queensland Australian Football League]]\n| firstseason        = 1999\n| ground             = McCarthy Homes Sherwood AFC, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]]\n| song               = Good Old Sherwood Club Forever\n| president          = Bruce McNichoal\n| coach              = Glenn Humphrey\n| captain            = Lachlan Woods\n| season             = 2016\n| premierships    = \n| kit_alt1        = \n| pattern_b1      = _portadelaide_bars\n| pattern_sh1     = \n| pattern_so1     = \n| body1           = ffffff\n| shorts1         = 000000\n| socks1          = 000000\n| pattern_name1   = <!--optional, default: Home -->\n| kit_alt2        = \n| pattern_b2      = \n| pattern_sh2     = \n| pattern_so2     = \n| body2           = \n| shorts2         = \n| socks2          = \n| pattern_name2   = <!--optional, default: Away -->\n  | url       = [http://www.westernmagpies.com.au/ westernmagpies.com.au]\n  | jumper     =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club''' is the senior [[Australian rules football]] club of the western suburbs of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]] which competes in Division One of the [[AFL Queensland State League|AFLQ State League]]. The club is based at McCarthy Homes Oval, 41 Chelmer st, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]],<ref name=\"fullpointsfooty.net\">http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/western_magpies.htm Sherwood Magpies</ref> at the same grounds as the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]] and fields a team in the [[AFLQ]] senior, reserve, under 18 and women's grade competitions. The Western Magpies AFC provides a focal point for talented players from all of the junior clubs that lie within [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane's]] western suburbs (Collingwood Park, Ferny Grove, Forest Lake, Kenmore, Jindalee, Moorooka, Sherwood, Southern Redbacks, Springfield Lakes, Wests Juniors, Yeronga). The club aims to provide a pathway into the [[Australian Football League|AFL]] for players from these junior clubs, develop the network of surrounding senior and junior [[Australian rules football]] clubs, and provide a fun, friendly, family oriented hub for local football in the western suburbs.<ref>http://www.sherwoodafc.com/inside.htm A Brief History of the Black & White</ref> The '''Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club''' and [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]] are sponsored by Tradelink (major sponsor), [[Hog's Breath Cafe]] and Cleanway (secondary sponsors).<ref>http://www.sherwoodafc.com/sponsors.htm Magpie Sponsors</ref>\n\nThere have been a number of senior clubs ([[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa]], [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]], [[Sherwood Australian Football Club|Sherwood]], and [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club|West Brisbane]]) based within the western suburbs of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]] that have competed in the highest division of local football. These clubs were all forced out of existence over time, and the Sherwood Magpies AFC resembles a culmination of the area's historical and continuing football presence and strength. The current club has been playing in Division Two of the [[AFL Queensland State League]] since 2004, but is being promoted into Division One from the commencement of the 2009 season under the guidance of President Brian Knight, Senior Coach Paul Grentell and Club Development Manager Anthony McDonald.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?c=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6786642 Anthony McDonald Joins Magpies</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Sherwood Magpies Australian Football Club was formed as the State League representative of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs, incorporating the history of the previous clubs to compete in the [[AFL Queensland State League]].\n\n===Taringa AFC===\nA '''Taringa Football Club''' competed in the QFL (an early form of the [[AFL Queensland State League]]) in the 1920 season. The club only appeared in the State competition for that single season, but resurfaced by entering the newly titled [[QANFL]] in 1931. The club's emblem was the [[bulldog]], and the club colours were maroon and white. Despite making it to five grand finals '''Taringa''' was unable to secure a premiership, but it produced two [[De Little Medal]]ists in C.Vigden (1939) and Doug Pittard (1940). '''Taringa''' changed its name to the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club]] in 1946.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/western_districts.htm Western Districts</ref>\n\n===Western Districts AFC===\nThe '''Western Districts Australian Football Club''' came into existence in 1946 when the [[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa Football Club]] changed its name to incorporate the whole of [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs. '''Western Districts''' kept the emblem (the [[bulldog]]) and colours (maroon and white) of [[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa]] and were originally based at Oakman Park, [[Toowong, Queensland|Toowong]] but moved to Chelmer Oval, Queenscroft st, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]] in 1971. The club continued to grow steadily, finishing in third place in 1951, and losing to [[Mayne Australian Football Club|Mayne]] by merely one point in the 1952 grand final. The club learned from their narrow loss, defeating Windsor and Sandgate respectively in the 1953 and 1954 grand finals to secure their first and second premierships. '''Western Districts''' were unable to qualify for the finals between the years of 1956 and 1962, before suffering consecutive grand final losses at the hands of [[Mayne Australian Football Club|Mayne]] in 1966 and 1967. The club's next, and last ever, grand final appearances came consecutively in 1977, 1978 and 1979. The '''Bulldogs''' narrowly won premierships by 5 points against Wilston Grange in 1977, and by 4 points against [[Zillmere Eagles Australian Football Club|Windsor/Zillmere]] in 1978, before losing what would be their last grand final appearance to [[Sandgate Australian Football Club|Sandgate]] in 1979. '''Western Districts''' eventually merged with [[Sherwood Australian Football Club|Sherwood]] in 1991 to form the [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club]]. The '''Western Districts Australian Football Club''' had a number of very successful players in their midst throughout their existence. Doug Pittard won two [[Grogan Medal]]s during his time at the club to go with his [[De Little Medal]] he won with [[Taringa Australian Football Club|Taringa]], and played a handful of games for the [[Footscray Football Club|Footscray]] reserves. Owen Backwell was also a dual [[Grogan Medal]]ist for the '''Bulldogs''', who topped the league goal kicking in 1977, played over 300 games for the club, including the 1977 and 1978 premierships, and had a short stint with the [[Fitzroy Football Club]]. Ray Hughson topped the league goal kicking while playing for [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]] a remarkable six times (1958, 1959, 1962\u201365), while [[Gavin Crosisca]] (over 250 [[Australian Football League|AFL]] games for [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]]), Ray Smith (over 100 [[Australian Football League|VFL]] games for [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]] and [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne]]), and Gary Shaw ([[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood]] and the [[Brisbane Bears]], and still coaches at the Western Magpies) all went on to play in the [[Australian Football League|VFL/AFL]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /><ref>http://www.footypedia.com/00000517.htm Western Districts Football Club</ref>\n\n===Sherwood AFC===\nThe '''Sherwood Australian Football Club''' developed out of the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]], which was formed in 1956. As the junior club grew in size, there was a desire to have a direct senior team for the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club|Sherwood JAFC]], which saw the '''Sherwood AFC''' formed to compete in the Metropolitan Division of the [[AFL Queensland State League|QAFL]]. The club was based at Chelmer Oval, 41 Chelmer st, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]], directly next to the Queenscroft st ground of the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]], which is the current home of the Western Magpies. The club took on the black and white stripes of their junior club as well as the emblem of the [[magpie]], both of which are still thoroughly attached to the club to the current day thanks to the winning of a coin toss with [[Southport Australian Football Club|Southport]] (who had previously had the same colours and emblem) upon the entry of both clubs to the [[AFL Queensland State League|QAFL]] in 1983. This occurred after '''Sherwood''' managed to work their way up through the divisions, after winning eight first division flags in a row they earned their 1983 promotion into the [[AFL Queensland State League|QAFL]]. In 1991 '''Sherwood AFC''' merged with the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts]] to form the [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club]], which could be a single footballing force in [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs. Players of particular note for the '''Sherwood AFC''' include [[John Rantall]], the 336 game [[Sydney Swans|South Melbourne]], [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] and [[Fitzroy Football Club|Fitzroy]] [[Australian Football League|VFL]] veteran who coached '''Sherwood''' in their debut season in the [[QAFL]], and 1983 [[Grogan Medal]] winner, Bill Pierce, whom the Western Magpies best and fairest is named after.<ref name=\"sherwoodafc.com\">http://www.sherwoodafc.com/inside.htm A Brief History Of The Black & White</ref>\n\n===West Brisbane AFC===\nA merger between the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club|Western Districts AFC]] and the [[Sherwood Australian Football Club|Sherwood AFC]] in 1991 saw a single senior force in the western suburbs formed in the form of the '''West Brisbane Australian Football Club'''. The merged club adopted the maroon and white colours of [Western Districts Australian Football Club] with the jersey design of the Port Adelaide Magpies football club, played out of Chelmer Oval, [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]] and were nicknamed The '''Warriors'''. The club was successful in winning a premiership in the 1996 season, comfortably defeating [[Mt Gravatt Australian Football Club|Mt Gravatt]] 17.10 (112) to 8.10 (58), with Corey Lambert claiming that year's [[Grogan Medal]]. Unfortunately, due to financial reasons '''West Brisbane''' were unable to compete in the following year's competition and had a few seasons out of the State competition before returning as the re-branded Western Magpies Australian Football Club in 2001.<ref name=\"fullpointsfooty.net\" /><ref>http://www.footypedia.com/00000512.htm West Brisbane Football Club</ref>\n\n===The Current Club===\n\nThe [[West Brisbane Australian Football Club]] that disbanded at the end of 1997 reformed in 1999 under the name of the Western Magpies Australian Football Club and in 2001 re-entered the [[QAFL]]<ref name=\"fullpointsfooty.net\" /> which had merged with its [[Gold Coast, Australia|Gold Coast]] equivalent to become the [[AFL Queensland State League]]. After four years of mediocre on-field performances and financial struggles, when the [[AFL Queensland|AFLQ]] decided to undertake a major re-shuffling of the leagues in 2004 to create a two tier [[AFL Queensland|State League]] competition the Western Magpies were relegated to the newly created Division Two. Paul Grentell was appointed the club's senior coach, and the '''Magpies''' set about strengthening every aspect of the football club in the hopes of returning to Division One. The senior team narrowly missed out on a place in the 2005 Division Two grand final, but were successful in reaching the grand final in 2006, 2007 and 2008. The Western Magpies defeated the [[Noosa Australian Football Club|Noosa Tigers]] in the 2006 decider, before losing to the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] in the final game of 2007. Despite losing the 2007 grand final, it was announced at the end of that year that the Western Magpies would be returning to Division One of the [[AFL Queensland State League|State League]] in 2009. The Magpies rebounded from their 2007 loss to [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach]] to end the Lions 38-game winning streak at their [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]] home ground during the 2008 home and away season, and followed this up by defeating the Lions again in a thrilling grand final.<ref name=\"sportingpulse.com\">http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6798374&sectionID=56344 Western Magpies Win 2008 Div 2 Premiership</ref> This capped the club's time in Division Two off nicely, leaving them with two premierships (2006 & 2008) and three grand final appearances (2006\u20132008) from their four years in lower division. During this four-year period, the reserves team played in the Division Two grand final (each year 2005\u20132008), winning premierships in 2005, 2006 and 2007, while the under 18 and women's teams both continued to participate in Division One of their competitions.\n\nAs of the beginning of Season 2020 in the Queensland Australian Football League \n\n==Links To Other Local Clubs==\nThe Western Magpies enjoy close relationships with all of the junior and senior clubs within [[Brisbane, Australia|Brisbane]]'s western suburbs in their role as the focal point for football ball in the area. All junior clubs within the area are encouraged to promote the Western Magpies as the pathway into the [[Australian Football League|AFL]] for young players in the western suburbs. In a similar way, the club also relates closely with the surrounding senior clubs, as they also provide a pathway for players to play at a standard of football that best suits their ability.<ref name=\"sherwoodafc.com\" /> In particular, the Western Magpies work closely with the [[Sherwood Junior Australian Football Club]] and the [[Kenmore Australian Football Club]]. The junior clubs within the western suburbs that the Western Magpies work with include;\n*Collingwood Park\n*Ferny Grove\n*Forest Lake\n*The Gap\n*Kenmore\n*Jindalee\n*Moggill\n*Moorooka\n*Park Ridge\n*Sherwood\n*Southern Redbacks\n*Springfield Lakes\n*Wests Juniors\n*Yeronga\n\n===Sherwood Junior AFC===\nThe senior Western Magpies club is based out of the same grounds and facilities as the Sherwood Junior AFC. The two clubs are both affiliated with the Sherwood Football social club, and Sherwood Junior AFC acts as one of the many local feeder clubs to the Western Magpies, with many juniors moving up from the Sherwood juniors into the senior club. The '''Sherwood Junior AFC''''s aim is to produce quality players to graduate into football with the Western Magpies, and eventually to the [[Australian Football League|AFL]].<ref name=\"sherwoodafc.com\" /> The official website of the '''Sherwood Junior AFC''' is located at [http://www.sherwoodafc.com/ www.sherwoodafc.com].\n\n===Kenmore AFC===\nThe [[Kenmore Australian Football Club]] are a separate club who play in the [http://www.aflq.com.au/index.php?id=911 QFA South competition].[[Kenmore Australian Football Club|The Kenmore Bears]] and the Western Magpies enjoy a close relationship that sees players transfer between the two clubs in order to play the best possible level of football. The two clubs' grounds are situated next to each other in [[Chelmer, Queensland|Chelmer]], with [[Kenmore Australian Football Club|Kenmore]] playing out of the Queenscroft st grounds that were once those of the [[Western Districts Australian Football Club]]. In 2008 these grounds were closed for redevelopment, and [[Kenmore Australian Football Club|Kenmore]] played their all of their home games for that season on the Western Magpies field.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-4711-0-0-0&sID=56333&articleID=5033895&news_task=DETAIL New Alliance Ensures Bright Future</ref> The official website of the [[Kenmore Australian Football Club|Kenmore Bears]] is located at [http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?sportid=4&client=1-109-37543-0-0 www.kenmore.aflq.com.au].\n\n==2008 season==\nThe Western Magpies Australian Football Club competed in the Pineapple Hotel Cup in 2008, the Division Two competition of the [[AFL Queensland State League]]. The president for 2008 was Matthew Vowles, who entered the position in 2007, and the captain Chris Mihalopolous, a junior of the '''Sherwood Junior AFC'''. Paul Grentell, who took over the position as senior coach in 2004, was to coach the senior team in 2008, assisted by Peter McClennan (reserves coach), Hadyn Dowley, Quentin Johnson and Brian Millar. After being defeated by the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club]] in the 2007 grand final, the Western Magpies went through the 2008 home and away season with fifteen wins out of eighteen games to sit second on the ladder to the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] before the commencement of the finals series.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/team_info.cgi?c=1-109-34766-65372-6259025&a=ROUND Pineapple Hotel Cup Seniors Results 2008</ref> The Magpies's only losses were against [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin]] (Round 1), [[Coolangatta Tweed Heads Football Club|Coolangatta Tweed Head]] (Round 2) and [[Burleigh Football Club|Burleigh]] (Round 16), and one of the most memorable victories came in Round 14, when the Magpies defeated the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] 18.8 (116) to 5.16 (46) to end the Lions's 34-game winning streak.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-4711-0-0-0&sID=56333&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=5911606 Magpies Make A Statement</ref> The Western Magpies and the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Palm Beach Currumbin Lions]] both made it through the finals series into the 2008 [[AFL Queensland State League]] grand final for a rematch of the previous year's grand final. The two clubs fought out a tough contest, which saw the [[Palm Beach Currumbin Australian Football Club|Lions]] lead throughout the first three quarters of the game. The Magpies lifted during the third quarter to close in on the minor premiers, and managed to kick six goals to two in a thrilling final quarter to take out a nail biting decider, 16.8 (104) to 14.17 (101).<ref>http://westside-news.whereilive.com.au/sport/story/pies-in-upset-finals-victory/ Pies In Upset Finals Victory</ref> The Magpies reserves went through the home and away season with only two losses, to Wilston Grange and [[Burleigh Australian Football Club|Burleigh]]. This left the team on top of the ladder, one game clear of their closest rivals.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/comp_info.cgi?a=LADDER&round=18&client=1-109-0-66115-0&pool=1 Pineapple Hotel Cup Reserves Ladder Round 18 2008</ref> The reserves won their way straight through to the grand final, where they were unable to make it four consecutive Division Two premierships, being soundly beaten by [[Aspley Australian Football Club|Aspley]] 10.8 (68) to 21.7 (133).<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/comp_info.cgi?c=1-109-0-66115-0&pool=1001&round=18&a=ROUND Pineapple Hotel Cup Reserves Finals Round 6 Results 2008</ref> The Western Magpies under 18 team won three of their matches curing the season, and were unable to secure a place in the finals.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/comp_info.cgi?a=LADDER&round=16&client=1-109-0-69696-0&pool=1 Under 18 Division One Ladder Round 16 2008</ref>\n\n===Award Winners===\n\nThe following awards were presented at the Western Magpies Australian Football Club presentation night on 18 October.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6919627&sectionID=56344</ref>\n\n====Seniors====\n\n*Bill Pierce Medal for Best & Fairest \u2013 Val Pope\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Richard Wenham\n*Most Consistent \u2013 Greg Friis\n*BG Award \u2013 Tim McEvoy\n*Rookie of the Year \u2013 Gerard Moore\n*Best Back \u2013 Mark Dowley\n*Best Midfielder \u2013 Richard Wenham\n*Best Forward \u2013 Adam Gillespie\n*Best Finals Player \u2013 Luke Scott\n*Best on Ground in the Grand Final \u2013 James Rozynski\n\n====Reserves====\n*Best & Fairest \u2013 Jye Spencer\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Blake McClennan\n*Most Consistent \u2013 Luke Knight\n*Most Improved Player \u2013 Dominic Beer\n*Best Back \u2013 Scott Hughes\n*Best Midfielder \u2013 Matthew Page\n*Best Forward \u2013 Jay Baker\n*Best Finals Player \u2013 Cameron Thomas\n\n====Under 18====\n*Maurie McNamee Medal for Best & Fairest \u2013 Mark Stratton\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Daniel Massey\n*Most Consistent \u2013 Cory Colhoun\n*Most Improved \u2013 Jordan Patterson\n*Encouragement Award \u2013 Matthew Green\n*Russell Green Memorial Trophy for Coach of the Year \u2013 [[Gary Shaw (Australian footballer)|Gary Shaw]]\n\n==2009 season==\n\nIt was announced at the end of 2007 that the Western Magpies would be returning to Division One of the [[AFL Queensland State League]] from 2009.<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-4711-0-0-0&sID=56333&articleID=4885742&news_task=DETAIL Western Magpies Set FOr 2009 Return To State League</ref> After achieving successful results, it was felt that the Magpies had made enough progress to warrant a western suburbs presence in the State League. In 2008 the club hired Anthony McDonald as Club Development Officer to assist in the progression up to the [[AFL Queensland State League|State League]],<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?c=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=6786642 Anthony McDonald Joins The Magpies</ref> and began interviewing potential players to bolster their playing list for the 2009 season. The club's existing young talent was bolstered by the signings of 2007 Tasmanian under 18 representative Matt Dillon <ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=7030105&sectionID=56344 Tassie Magpie Becomes QLD Magpie</ref> and former [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] rookie and Western Magpie junior Ed McDonnell<ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34766-0-0&sID=56344&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=7080688&sectionID=56344 Former St Kilda Rookie Returns To Magpies Nest</ref> but overall the Magpies failed to recruit many top level players. The Western Magpies senior squad were put through a tough pre-season program before hosting the [[Redland Australian Football Club|Redland Bombers]] in round one of the season. The Magpies seniors team were unable to get a victory in their first match in the [[AFL Queensland State League]], losing by 48 points in a match that has so far set the tone for their season. The Western Magpies seniors are currently yet to record a victory in the 2009 season, as seen in the table of results below;\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Round\n! Venue\n! Opposition\n! Magpies Score\n! Opposition Score\n|-\n| 1\n| Chelmer\n| [[Redland Australian Football Club|Redland]]\n| 11.7.73\n| 17.19.121\n|-\n| 2\n| Cooke-Murphy Oval\n| [[Labrador Australian Football Club|Labrador Tigers]]\n| 4.6.30\n| 22.19.151\n|-\n| 3\n| Chelmer\n| [[Broadbeach Australian Football Club|Broadbeach Cats]]\n| 15.6.96\n| 21.11.137\n|-\n| 4\n| Fankhauser Reserve\n| [[Southport Australian Football Club|Southport Sharks]]\n| 2.7.19\n| 28.12.180\n|-\n| 5\n| Chelmer\n| [[Aspley Australian Football Club|Aspley Hornets]]\n| 17.9.111\n| 18.19.118\n|-\n| 6\n| Chelmer\n| [[Morningside Australian Football Club|Morningside Panthers]]\n| 10.7.67\n| 31.13.199\n|-\n| 7\n| [[Traeger Park]]\n| [[Northern Territory Football Club|Northern Territory Thunder]]\n| 6.7.43\n| 26.13.169\n|-\n| 8\n| Chelmer\n| [[Brisbane Lions]]\n| 11.10.76\n| 16.9.105\n|-\n| 9\n| Esplen Oval\n| [[Morningside Australian Football Club|Morningside Panthers]]\n| 5.5.35\n| 27.21.183\n|-\n| 10\n| Dittmer Park\n| [[Mt Gravatt Australian Football Club|Mount Gravatt Vultures]]\n| 4.5.29\n| 25.16.166\n|-\n| 11\n| Chelmer\n| [[Northern Territory Football Club|Northern Territory Thunder]]\n| 10.11.71\n| 16.16.112\n|-\n| 12\n| Chelmer\n| [[Labrador Australian Football Club|Labrador Tigers]]\n| 14.10.94\n| 18.12.120\n|-\n| 13\n| Merrimac Oval\n| [[Broadbeach Australian Football Club|Broadbeach Cats]]\n| 6.10.46\n| 15.18.108\n|-\n| 14\n| Graham Rd\n| [[Aspley Australian Football Club|Aspley Hornets]]\n| 12.9.81\n| 20.13.133\n|-\n| 15\n| Chelmer\n| [[Southport Australian Football Club|Southport Sharks]]\n| 5.7.37\n| 15.20.110\n|-\n| 16\n| Chelmer\n| [[Mt Gravatt Australian Football Club|Mount Gravatt Vultures]]\n| 12.8.80\n| 17.12.144\n|-\n| 17\n| Victoria Point Oval\n| [[Redland Australian Football Club|Redland]]\n| 12.7.79\n| 15.16.106\n|-\n| 18\n| [[The Gabba]]\n| [[Brisbane Lions]]\n| 8.11.59\n| 32.19.211\n|}\n\n===Seniors Awards===\n\n*Bill Pierce Medal for Best & Fairest \u2013 Ben Heffernan-Roper\n*Runner-Up Best & Fairest \u2013 Chris Judson\n*BG Award \u2013 Luke Scott\n*Rookie of the Year \u2013 Ben Jaenke-Cain\n*Best Back \u2013 Ed McDonnell\n*Best Midfielder \u2013 Ben Heffernan-Roper\n*Best Forward \u2013 Josh Barton\n*Hard luck story - Chris McClennan\n\n==Honour List==\n\n=== Senior Premierships===\n\n'''Queensland Australian Football League''' <ref name=\"ReferenceB\">http://www.fullpointsfooty.net/qafl_summary_chart.htm QAFL Summary Chart</ref>\n\n*1953 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1954 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1977 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1978 \u2013 Western Districts\n*1996 \u2013 West Brisbane\n\n'''AFL Queensland State League \u2013 Division Two'''\n\n*2006 \u2013 Western Magpies <ref>http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=1-109-34756-0-0&sID=55272&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=4873326&sectionID=55272 Tigers Go Down Fighting In Grand Finals</ref>\n*2008 \u2013 Western Magpies <ref name=\"sportingpulse.com\" />\n\n'''SEQAFL Division One - PHC'''\n*''2012''\n\n===AFL/VFL Listed Players===\n\n*[[Ray Smith (Australian footballer)|Ray Smith]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon Bombers]] (1971\u20131975, 77 games 1 goal), [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne Demons]] (1975\u20131976, 27 games 1 goal)\n*[[Gary Shaw (Australian footballer)|Gary Shaw]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood Magpies]] (1983\u20131986, 32 games 33 goals), [[Brisbane Bears]] (1987, 6 games 5 goals)\n*[[Craig Potter (Australian footballer)|Craig Potter]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Sydney Swans]] (1984\u20131990, 42 games 16 goals) [[Brisbane Bears]] (1991\u20131993, 13 games 3 goals)\n*[[Gavin Crosisca]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Collingwood Football Club|Collingwood Magpies]] (1987\u20132000, 246 games 64 goals)\n*[[Simon Luhrs]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Brisbane Bears]] (1991\u20131993, 12 games 0 goals)\n*[[Simon Hose]] (Western Districts) \u2013 [[Sydney Swans]] (1986\u20131988, 0 games 0 goals) [[Brisbane Bears]] (1989\u2013199