{"title_page": "Peter Westgarth", "text_new": "'''Peter Allen Westgarth''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CVO}} was the chief executive, [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] (DofE) and former chief executive of [[Young Enterprise UK]], Oxford.<ref name=\"gazette\">\"[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/57962/supplement/5/data.pdf The Queen\u2019s Award for Enterprise Promotion]\", (21 April 2006). ''[[The London Gazette]]'',  Supplement No. 1, pS5. Retrieved 23 November 2015.</ref> In 2006, he was awarded the [[Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2006)|Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion]].[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/57962/supplement/5/data.pdf The Queen\u2019s Award for Enterprise Promotion]\", (21 April 2006). ''[[The London Gazette]]'',  Supplement No. 1, pS5. Retrieved 23 November 2015.</ref>\n\nWestgarth joined The Duke of Edinburgh's Award in 2005 and oversaw a complete rebrand, leaving in 2019.<ref name=\"dofe\">\"[http://www.dofe.info/en/content/cms/about-us/executive-team/ Our Executive Management Team]\", ''[[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]]''. Retrieved 23 November 2015.</ref> He was appointed [[Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] (CVO) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N5|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westgarth, Peter}}\n[[Category:Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2006)]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n\n\n{{UK-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Peter Allen Westgarth''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CVO}} was the chief executive, [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] (DofE) and former chief executive of [[Young Enterprise UK]], Oxford.<ref name=\"gazette\">\"[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/57962/supplement/5/data.pdf The Queen\u2019s Award for Enterprise Promotion]\", (21 April 2006). ''[[The London Gazette]]'',  Supplement No. 1, pS5. Retrieved 23 November 2015.</ref> In 2006, he was awarded the [[Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2006)|Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion]].[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/57962/supplement/5/data.pdf The Queen\u2019s Award for Enterprise Promotion]\", (21 April 2006). ''[[The London Gazette]]'',  Supplement No. 1, pS5. Retrieved 23 November 2015.</ref>\n\nWestgarth joined The Duke of Edinburgh's Award in 2005 and oversaw a complete rebrand, leaving in 2019.<ref name=\"dofe\">\"[http://www.dofe.info/en/content/cms/about-us/executive-team/ Our Executive Management Team]\", ''[[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award]]''. Retrieved 23 November 2015.</ref> He was appointed [[Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]] (CVO) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N5|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westgarth, Peter}}\n[[Category:Queen's Award for Enterprise Promotion (2006)]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n\n\n{{UK-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Westgarth"}
{"title_page": "The Westland", "text_new": "{{about|the former train service in Western Australia|the current train service in Queensland|The Westlander|the Rail Heritage WA magazine|The Westland (periodical)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox rail service\n|box_width       = \n|name            = The Westland\n|logo            = \n|logo_width      = \n|image           = X1001 Yalagonga, 1954.jpg\n|image_size      =\n|caption         = [[WAGR X class|X1001]] with a ''Westland'' nameplate in 1954\n|type            = Overnight passenger train\n|status          = Ceased\n|locale          = \n|predecessor     = \n|first           = 4 June 1938\n|last            = 15 June 1969\n|successor       = [[Trans Australian]]\n|operator        = \n|formeroperator  = [[Western Australian Government Railways]]\n|ridership       = \n|start           = [[Perth railway station|Perth]]\n|stops           = \n|end             = [[Kalgoorlie railway station|Kalgoorlie]]\n|distance        = \n|journeytime     =\n|frequency       = 3 x per week\n|trainnumber     = 83/84\n|line_used       = [[Eastern Railway (Western Australia)|Eastern]]<br>[[Eastern Goldfields Railway|Eastern Goldfields]]\n|class           = First & second\n|access          = \n|seating         = \n|catering        = \n|entertainment   = \n|baggage         = \n|otherfacilities = \n|stock           = \n|gauge           = \n|speed           = \n|owners          = \n|routenumber     = \n|map             = }}\n\n'''''The Westland''''' was the name given in 1938 to the overnight train operated by the [[Western Australian Government Railways]] (WAGR) with sitting and [[sleeping car]]s between [[Perth railway station|Perth]] and [[Kalgoorlie railway station|Kalgoorlie]], where it connected with the ''[[Trans-Australian]]'' service to [[Adelaide railway station|Adelaide]].\n\n==History==\nFollowing the opening of the [[Eastern Goldfields Railway]] to [[Kalgoorlie railway station|Kalgoorlie]] in December 1887, a service from [[Perth railway station|Perth]] commenced. Although not named, it was often referred to as the ''Great Eastern Express'', ''Kalgoorlie Express'' or ''Kalgoorlie Passenger''.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Australian Railway Historical Society, Western Australian Division|title=The Kalgoorlie, 1897-1971|publication-date=1971|publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society, WA Division|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/13550930|accessdate=23 March 2013}} at the cessation of the service in 1971, the ARHS pamphlet has (p.12) ''over the years the train has been named the Kalgoorlie Express, and in latter years The Kalgoorlie'', (and was locally known as the ''Kal'') see also {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article83884001|title=Kalgoorlie Express|newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]]|location=Perth|date=30 May 1932|accessdate=23 March 2013|page=4 Edition: Home(Final) edition |publisher=National Library of Australia}} and {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31259273|title=Kalgoorlie Express Late|newspaper=[[The West Australian]]|location=Perth|date=20 October 1924|accessdate=23 March 2013|page=7|publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the opening of the [[Trans-Australian Railway]] in October 1917, its importance increased with the commencement of the ''[[Trans-Australian|Trans-Australian Express]]'' from [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]] in [[South Australia]]. By May 1921, a separate overnight express for interstate passengers and mail was introduced and this became the connecting train with the ''Trans-Australian Express''.<ref name=ONock>{{cite book|last1=Nock|first1=Oswald|title=Railways of Australia|date=1971|publisher=Adam & Charles Black|location=London|isbn=0 7136 1190 1|pages=100, 253}}</ref><ref name=GHigham>{{cite book|last1=Higham|first1=Geoffrey|title=Marble Bar to Mandurah: A history of passenger rail services in Western Australia|date=2007|publisher=Rail Heritage WA|location=Bassendean|isbn=978 0 9803922 0 3|pages=107, 109, 110, 129, 130, 195}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 1938, the service was relaunched and renamed ''The Westland'' with [[WAGR P and Pr classes|Pr class]] locomotives rostered.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42084129 \"Westland\" enters service] ''[[The West Australian]]'' 4 June 1938</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gunzburg|first1=Adrian|title=A History of WAGR Steam Locomotives|date=1984|publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society|location=Perth|isbn=0 9599690 3 9|page=104}}</ref> It included sitting and sleeping cars (both first and second class). A [[dining car]] was attached between Perth and [[Northam railway station, Western Australia|Northam]] where it was detached having served dinner on the eastbound service. It was then attached to the westbound service for breakfast. [[Refreshment room]]s were also provided at major stations for passengers wishing to purchase cheaper snacks and drinks. [[World War II]] austerity measures saw the lounge cars removed until March 1946. On 28 March 1948, it was again relaunched with new AH class steel sleeping carriages with the other carriages refurbished.<ref name=GHigham/><ref name=GrayMay>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Bill|last2=May|first2=Andrew|title=A History of WAGR Passenger Carriages|date=2006|publisher=Bill Gray|location=Perth|isbn=0-646-45902-3|pages=185, 262, 263}}</ref> This was to be the last improvement to the train, although the introduction of the [[WAGR X class|X class]] [[diesel-electric locomotive]]s in 1954 marginally reduced traveling time.\n\n==Demise==\nWith the line between Perth and Kalgoorlie [[Track gauge conversion|gauge converted]] to [[Eastern Railway (Western Australia)#Third Route|standard gauge]], ''The Westland'' was replaced on 15 June 1969 by the ''[[Trans Australian]]'' which now operated from [[Port Pirie Junction railway station|Port Pirie]] through to [[East Perth railway station|East Perth]].<ref name=ONock/><ref name=GrayMay/> Right up to that time drinking water in the second class sleepers was provided for passengers from water bags slung from the carriage platform railing, and a stack of fire wood was kept on the platform of the dining car to fuel its stoves.\n\nThe standard gauge line followed a [[Eastern Railway (Western Australia)#Third Route|new alignment]] through the [[Avon River (Western Australia)|Avon Valley]] of the [[Darling Scarp]] east of Perth. This was the first section of the new line to be constructed, tracks on this section being [[dual gauge]] (1067 and 1435mm). For a short time before its demise, ''The Westland'' was routed via the new Avon Valley line, and the original ascent of the Darling Scarp via the [[Swan View Tunnel]] and [[Chidlow]] was closed.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westland}}\n[[Category:Kalgoorlie-Boulder]]\n[[Category:Named passenger trains of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1938]]\n[[Category:Railway services discontinued in 1969]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:1969 disestablishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Night trains of Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2014}}\n{{about|the former train service in Western Australia|the current train service in Queensland|The Westlander|the Rail Heritage WA magazine|The Westland (periodical)}}\n{{Infobox rail service\n|box_width       = \n|name            = The Westland\n|logo            = \n|logo_width      = \n|image           = X1001 Yalagonga, 1954.jpg\n|image_size      =\n|caption         = [[WAGR X class|X1001]] with a ''Westland'' nameplate in 1954\n|type            = Overnight passenger train\n|status          = Ceased\n|locale          = \n|predecessor     = \n|first           = 4 June 1938\n|last            = 15 June 1969\n|successor       = [[Trans Australian]]\n|operator        = \n|formeroperator  = [[Western Australian Government Railways]]\n|ridership       = \n|start           = [[Perth railway station|Perth]]\n|stops           = \n|end             = [[Kalgoorlie railway station|Kalgoorlie]]\n|distance        = \n|journeytime     =\n|frequency       = 3 x per week\n|trainnumber     = 83/84\n|line_used       = [[Eastern Railway (Western Australia)|Eastern]]<br>[[Eastern Goldfields Railway|Eastern Goldfields]]\n|class           = First & second\n|access          = \n|seating         = \n|catering        = \n|entertainment   = \n|baggage         = \n|otherfacilities = \n|stock           = \n|gauge           = \n|speed           = \n|owners          = \n|routenumber     = \n|map             = }}\n\n'''''The Westland''''' was the name given in 1938 to the overnight train operated by the [[Western Australian Government Railways]] (WAGR) with sitting and [[sleeping car]]s between [[Perth railway station|Perth]] and [[Kalgoorlie railway station|Kalgoorlie]], where it connected with the ''[[Trans-Australian]]'' service to [[Adelaide railway station|Adelaide]].\n\n==History==\nFollowing the opening of the [[Eastern Goldfields Railway]] to [[Kalgoorlie railway station|Kalgoorlie]] in December 1887, a service from [[Perth railway station|Perth]] commenced. Although not named, it was often referred to as the ''Great Eastern Express'', ''Kalgoorlie Express'' or ''Kalgoorlie Passenger''.<ref>{{Citation|author1=Australian Railway Historical Society, Western Australian Division|title=The Kalgoorlie, 1897-1971|publication-date=1971|publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society, WA Division|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/13550930|accessdate=23 March 2013}} at the cessation of the service in 1971, the ARHS pamphlet has (p.12) ''over the years the train has been named the Kalgoorlie Express, and in latter years The Kalgoorlie'', (and was locally known as the ''Kal'') see also {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article83884001|title=Kalgoorlie Express|newspaper=[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]]|location=Perth|date=30 May 1932|accessdate=23 March 2013|page=4 Edition: Home(Final) edition |publisher=National Library of Australia}} and {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31259273|title=Kalgoorlie Express Late|newspaper=[[The West Australian]]|location=Perth|date=20 October 1924|accessdate=23 March 2013|page=7|publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the opening of the [[Trans-Australian Railway]] in October 1917, its importance increased with the commencement of the ''[[Trans-Australian|Trans-Australian Express]]'' from [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]] in [[South Australia]]. By May 1921, a separate overnight express for interstate passengers and mail was introduced and this became the connecting train with the ''Trans-Australian Express''.<ref name=ONock>{{cite book|last1=Nock|first1=Oswald|title=Railways of Australia|date=1971|publisher=Adam & Charles Black|location=London|isbn=0 7136 1190 1|pages=100, 253}}</ref><ref name=GHigham>{{cite book|last1=Higham|first1=Geoffrey|title=Marble Bar to Mandurah: A history of passenger rail services in Western Australia|date=2007|publisher=Rail Heritage WA|location=Bassendean|isbn=978 0 9803922 0 3|pages=107, 109, 110, 129, 130, 195}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 1938, the service was relaunched and renamed ''The Westland'' with [[WAGR P and Pr classes|Pr class]] locomotives rostered.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42084129 \"Westland\" enters service] ''[[The West Australian]]'' 4 June 1938</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gunzburg|first1=Adrian|title=A History of WAGR Steam Locomotives|date=1984|publisher=Australian Railway Historical Society|location=Perth|isbn=0 9599690 3 9|page=104}}</ref> It included sitting and sleeping cars (both first and second class). A [[dining car]] was attached between Perth and [[Northam railway station, Western Australia|Northam]] where it was detached having served dinner on the eastbound service. It was then attached to the westbound service for breakfast. [[Refreshment room]]s were also provided at major stations for passengers wishing to purchase cheaper snacks and drinks. [[World War II]] austerity measures saw the lounge cars removed until March 1946. On 28 March 1948, it was again relaunched with new AH class steel sleeping carriages with the other carriages refurbished.<ref name=GHigham/><ref name=GrayMay>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Bill|last2=May|first2=Andrew|title=A History of WAGR Passenger Carriages|date=2006|publisher=Bill Gray|location=Perth|isbn=0-646-45902-3|pages=185, 262, 263}}</ref> This was to be the last improvement to the train, although the introduction of the [[WAGR X class|X class]] [[diesel-electric locomotive]]s in 1954 marginally reduced traveling time.\n\n==Demise==\nWith the line between Perth and Kalgoorlie [[Track gauge conversion|gauge converted]] to [[Eastern Railway (Western Australia)#Third Route|standard gauge]], ''The Westland'' was replaced on 15 June 1969 by the ''[[Trans Australian]]'' which now operated from [[Port Pirie Junction railway station|Port Pirie]] through to [[East Perth railway station|East Perth]].<ref name=ONock/><ref name=GrayMay/> Right up to that time drinking water in the second class sleepers was provided for passengers from water bags slung from the carriage platform railing, and a stack of fire wood was kept on the platform of the dining car to fuel its stoves.\n\nThe standard gauge line followed a [[Eastern Railway (Western Australia)#Third Route|new alignment]] through the [[Avon River (Western Australia)|Avon Valley]] of the [[Darling Scarp]] east of Perth. This was the first section of the new line to be constructed, tracks on this section being [[dual gauge]] (1067 and 1435mm). For a short time before its demise, ''The Westland'' was routed via the new Avon Valley line, and the original ascent of the Darling Scarp via the [[Swan View Tunnel]] and [[Chidlow]] was closed.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westland}}\n[[Category:Kalgoorlie-Boulder]]\n[[Category:Named passenger trains of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1938]]\n[[Category:Railway services discontinued in 1969]]\n[[Category:1938 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:1969 disestablishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Night trains of Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Westland"}
{"title_page": "Westland Studios", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2016}}\n{{no footnotes|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Westland Studios\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = Westland Studios\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| trade_name = Westland Studios\n| native_name = Westland\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{Lang|[code]|[name]}} in native_name = and leave native_name_lang = empty. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = Lombard Sound Studios\n| type =\n| traded_as = Westland Studios Ltd, Westland Studios, Alwyn Walker T/A Westland Studios\n| ISIN = \n| ISIN2 = \n| industry = Audio\n| genre = \n| fate = closed 2018\n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], country --> 1985 in [[Dublin]]\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> Tom Costello, Brian Molloy\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> 2018\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = Tom Costello, Deirdre Costello, Brian Molloy, Alwyn Walker\n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = Recording, Mixing, Film Set\n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| aum = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| members = \n| members_year = <!-- Year of members data (if known) -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| ratio = <!-- Basel III ratio; used for banks only -->\n| rating = <!-- Credit rating; used for banks only -->\n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> www.westlandstudiosdublin.com\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n__NOTOC__\n'''Westland Studios''' was a recording studio located in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It was located on Lombard Street, less than a minute's walk from [[Dublin Pearse railway station|Pearse Station]]. It was opened in 1985 and closed in August 2018. Between 1985 and 2010 it was under the management of Tom Costello and his daughter Deirdre Costello and was leased out to producer and engineer Alwyn Walker from 2010 until its closure in 2018.\n\n==Early history==\nThe studio opened in 1976 under the name '''Lombard Sound''' and was the first 2 inch 24 track studio in Ireland. Briefly it was named '''Miracle Studios''' (as seen on the credits of the album \"Aliens\" by Horslips). It had a very large board of directors composed of recording artists, record label owner and artist managers. The studio ran under this format until 1984 when they sold all of the equipment and disbanded the company. Two of the directors (Tom Costello and Brian Molloy) of Lombard Sound took over the lease of the studio area and rebuilt the studio to a higher standard and extended the overall area of the studio facility. It re-opened quietly in October 1985 with its first session with Bill Whelan. Daire Winston was the house engineer at the time.\n\n==Past Clients==\nU2, Bob Dylan, Bryan Adams, The Corrs, Van Morrison, The Dubliners, The Mighty Stef, Cathy Davey, Hozier, Miley Cyrus, Phil Coulter, Aslan, Ryan Sheridan, Migos, J. Cole, Toucan, Elevation Falls and Tyler The Creator.\n\n==Fate==\nDespite the studio's popularity in 2018 due to rising rental costs in Dublin City the studio closed its doors marking the end of 42 years of music recording history. The rooms are currently used for podcast recordings by headstuff under the name \"The Podcast Studios\". Westland's former manager Alwyn Walker currently works as an online mix engineer.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Westland Studios}}\n*[http://www.westlandstudiosdublin.com/ Official Westland Studios website]\n*[http://www.thepodcaststudios.ie/en/ The Podcast Studios]\n*[http://www.alwynthemixengineer.com/ Alwyn The Mix Engineer]\n\n{{Coord|53|20.502|N|6|14.082|W|region:IE_type:landmark|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Recording studios in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Dublin (city)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=May 2016}}\n{{no footnotes|date=May 2016}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Westland Studios\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = Westland Studios\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| trade_name = Westland Studios\n| native_name = Westland\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{Lang|[code]|[name]}} in native_name = and leave native_name_lang = empty. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = Lombard Sound Studios\n| type =\n| traded_as = Westland Studios Ltd, Westland Studios, Alwyn Walker T/A Westland Studios\n| ISIN = \n| ISIN2 = \n| industry = Audio\n| genre = \n| fate = closed 2018\n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], country --> 1985 in [[Dublin]]\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> Tom Costello, Brian Molloy\n| defun